    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-12-22T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-12-22T05:00:00-05:00" n="130"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d130">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">660F.116/126: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Czechoslovakia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wright</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Prague</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-12-22T11:00:00+01:00"
                            >December 22, 1934—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 22—10:45 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>75. Department’s telegram No. 47, December 19, 7 [<hi rend="italic">6</hi>] p.m.
                    The Ministerial decree is based upon new Czechoslovak-German Clearing <pb
                        facs="0240" n="164" xml:id="pg_164"/> and Continuance [<hi rend="italic"
                        >sic</hi>] Agreement reported by Commercial Attaché in special report No.
                    74, November [28th], text of which was forwarded in same mail December 1st.<note
                        n="30" xml:id="d130fn30">Not found in Department riles.</note> The Governor
                    of Czechoslovak National Bank states that deduction of 4 percent is based upon
                    arbitrary assumption by Czech and German authorities that commission port
                    charges will equal that amount and that the arrangement is applicable to all
                    shipments of cotton via German ports irrespective of whether negotiated directly
                    or through German agents.</p>
                <p>In transactions where the agent in Germany signs the invoices it would seem that
                    the two countries are within their rights in this regard but any agreement
                    affecting the payments on commercial contracts with a third country wherein
                    German interest does not appear seems questionable from ethical and legal
                    standpoints.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wright</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
